Imagine a very long webpage with a lot of sections (i.e., an HTML specification on one page). If the user requests a particular section (e.g., page.html#section7), how would it be if the web server first streamed this section and then the other sections?
Streaming order:
1. Beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
Then the browser would make sure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed *above* section 7 on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible, without having to implement elements again with JavaScript. I simply want to have an extra-long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. With HTML, that should work.
The content could be streamed this way, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>s.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in order.
@user22 You can also rearrange documents without JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string search parameters so the server knows which section you want first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, but the browser then arranges the content in the DOM order.
The idea with slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 oh, do you want the browser to arrange the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, just so the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that were possible without influencing the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections were streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Take a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
